=== Searching for 0#nbb
- 0vbb search is basically looking for a mono-energetic peak at the end point of the 2vbb where all the energy is carried by the betas (the nuclear recoil energy is negligible),
- compared to 2vbb where most of the decay energy is transferred to the neutrinos.
- Easy to detect signal at Qbb
- If we see any events that belong to this decay, measure the half-life $t^(0nu)_(1"/"2) = ln 2 dot T epsilon thin N_(beta beta)/N_("peak")$
- The sensitivity of the detector depends crucially on the background, resolution and the exposure.
- The number of background events in the region is given by $Delta B $ (explain more of this )
- Sensitivity $S^(0 nu)_(1"/"2) = ln 2 dot epsilon (x eta)/n_sigma N_A/cal(M)_A (M T)/sqrt(M T Delta B)$,
- Sensitivity scales linearly with exposure when the $M T Delta B = O(1)$


=== Choice of isotope #te130 and bolometric method
- Optimization traingle of low energy particle detectors
  - Source mass - higher the expected decays, higher the possibility, is tied to isotop recovery cost given for most experiments a significant portion of cost is securing source materials with good enough quality.
  - Resolution - Good resolution is needed to see the monoenergetic peak at the edge, because the 2vbb cannot be suppressed.
  - Low background - Being able to destinguish from other backgrounds like the environment alphas and is important, ideally beta/gamma descrimination can get to almost 0 background.

- Choice of bolometric method in Te satisfy many of these requirements.
  - Bolomtric method shines in terms of resolution, very low intrinsic resolution, but the experimental resolution depends on other factors like externel noice etc. Also create higher complexity and need very low temperatures.
- High natural abundance of Te, coupled with feasibility of producing ultra-pure crystals at industrial scale is a major plus, reducing procurement costs. Already existing industrial capacity, and procedures for cleaneliness
- High $Q_(beta beta)$ reduces backgrounds even though #te130 bolometers lack any way to directly reduce backgrounds like in TPCs, and do not need extra detector setup like in LEGEND/GERDA.
  - high 2#nbb half-life helps with background too (though that might also increase the expected 0#nbb half life)

- Also #teo2 thermal expansion coefficient is close to that of Cu, making the construction of holders and assembly simpler.
- #teo2 can be leveraged with other detection methods like scintillation and cherenkov detection as initially done.   

